<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-214-796  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 214 796.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  April 17 1989 v8 n8 p101(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bush nominates Gen. Cassity to head C3 for Joint Chiefs. (James S.andO;Cassity Jr.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of DefenseMilitaryCommand and Control Systems.andO;Person:    Cassity, James S. (selection and appointment); Bush, George(staff).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Bush Nominates Gen.andP;  Cassity To Head C3 for Joint ChiefsandM;President Bush has nominated Maj.andP;  Gen.andP;  James S. Cassity Jr.andP;  as directorfor command, control and communications (C3) systems of the Joint Chiefs ofStaff at the Pentagon.andM;Cassity will replace Vice Adm.andP;  Jerry O. Tuttle in the post, which rotatesamong the services every two years.andP;  He must be confirmed by the Senate.andM;In his new post, Cassity will set Defense Department policy for military C3systems.andP;  Because of the tight budget climate, Cassity said he expects to &quot;besure that the commmand and control requirements that pass through me receivea careful look.&quot;andM;Cassity served one year as commander of the Air Force Communications Command(AFCC), where he oversaw the acquisition of mainly off-the-shelfcommunications and computer equipment and systems.andP;  Located at Scott AirForce Base, Ill., the AFCC manages all Air Force communications systems.andM;During Cassity's term in command, the AFCC oversaw the $929 million AFCAC 251acquisition.andP;  The contract for up to 21,000 minicomputers is possibly thelargest government contract for ADP equipment in history.andM;Before becoming AFCC commander, Cassity was director of systems integration,logistics and support for the U.S.andP;  Space Command and deputy chief of staffor systems integration, logistics and support for the Air Force SpaceCommand.andM;&quot;We'll be searching for smart, commonsense solutions, and obviously we'll bedepending on industry for concepts and ideas and equipment that are availableearly,&quot; Cassity said of his priorities in his new post.andM;&quot;I think we're going to see fewer long developmental programs.andP;  I think we'regoing to use more off-the-shelf items for command and control requirementsthroughout the DOD.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>